XPS data analysis provided valuable insight into the surface chemical composition, chemical valence, and chemical interactions of pure LFC0.5 and LFC0.5/G-CQDs composites (Fig. 3
                        ). The XPS survey spectra of pure LFC0.5 and LFC0.5/G-CQDs composites are displayed in Fig. 3a, indicating the existence of Cu 2p, Fe 2p, La 3d, C1s, and O1s (Fig. S2a). In comparison to pure LFC0.5, the XPS of LFC0.5/G-CQDs composites exhibited new N1s characteristic peaks. However, after doping, the C1s peaks' intensity was noticeably increased, proving that the LFC0.5 sample had been effectively doped with C and N elements. During hydrothermal reactions, the presence of hydroxyl groups in the reaction medium induced the formation of hydroxyl and other oxygen-containing groups on the surface of the material. The high-resolution C1s spectrum displayed three major peaks (Fig. 3a), where the binding energy at 284.8 eV was attributed to the CC/CC bonds and the binding energy at 285.95 eV and 288.95 eV were assigned to the COC and CO functional groups from carboxyl groups, respectively. The CC peaks shifted towards the lower energy side after the addition of G-CQDs. G-CQDs were effectively coupled into LFC0.5 as evidenced by the slight rise in the binding energies of CO and CC as a result of their interaction with the organic linker in LFC0.5. The high-resolution O1s spectra of the samples are shown in Fig. 3b. Two distinct peaks could be easily distinguished; the lower binding energy was attributed to the O2
                        − in the lattice oxygen at 528.5 eV, and the greater binding energy was attributed to the OVs at 530.6 eV. A comparison between the high-resolution spectra of O1s before and after doping revealed that the ratio of lattice oxygen species to defective oxygen species increased slightly after doping. In addition, the increase in defective oxygen may have been caused by an increase in crystal defects as a consequence of carbon and nitrogen doping [45]. The existence of a moderate number of defects is advantageous for the improvement of photocatalytic activity [46]. In the pure LFC0.5, the relative lattice oxygen and defective oxygen contents were 47.76 % and 52.24 %, respectively. The chemisorption of oxygen increased in the 530.6 eV peak's relative intensity in LFC0.5/G-CQD composites.

The absorption of light is one of the most important factors that determine the PEC performance of semiconductor materials. Therefore, the optical characteristics of pure LFC0.5 and LFC0.5/CQDs composites were investigated using UV–Vis DRS diffuse reflectance spectra. As anticipated, the absorption band edge of the multicolor fluorescent LFC0.5/CQDs composite appeared as follows (Fig. 4
                        a): LFC0.5/G-CQDs > LFC0.5/O-CQDs > LFC0.5/R-CQDs > LFC0.5/B-CQDs > LFC0.5/C-CQD. The order of the relative band gaps was as follows: 1.43 eV < 1.50 eV < 1.54 eV < 1.59 eV < 1.66 eV (Fig. 4b). The band gap of pure LFC0.5 was 1.85 eV. All of the LFC0.5/CQDs had a smaller band gap than LFC0.5, indicating that the doping of CQDs has significantly increased the light absorption range of LFC0.5. The generation of photogenerated carriers and the enhancement of optical absorption efficiency are both attributable to this increase in the range of light absorption. The decreased energy of band edge absorption was produced as a result of the formation of COFe bonds between CQDs and LFC0.5. This resulted in an effective enhancement of the availability of visible light and the powerful light absorption capabilities of CQDs. LFC0.5/G-CQDs had an absorption band edge of 720 nm, which was considerably greater than that of several other materials even though it had the smallest band gap. The absorption edge was redshifted due to the π-π* jump of the carbon–carbon double bond, indicating that the addition of G-CQDs increased the degree of conjugation in comparison to the luminescent quantum dot. The conversion and absorption of visible light were more favorable as the absorption range widened [47]. Furthermore, the superior electron transfer capabilities of G-CQDs can provide the double channels needed to transport photo-induced electrons. This could greatly improve the separation of charge carriers and the transfer of photo-induced electrons in LFC0.5/G-CQDs. The degradation performance of photocatalysts can be enhanced by a significant number of photoinduced electrons and holes. The electrochemical properties of CQDs and LFC0.5/G-CQDs composites were then examined to determine the impact of CQDs on the capability of LFC0.5 to transfer charges (Fig. 5
                        ).
